Metropolitan Bank, PLDT, Semirara: Philippine Stocks Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-04-18T01:18:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/metropolitan-bank-pldt-semirara-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.4 percent to
4,251.64.  Banks, Property: Funds sent home by overseas Filipinos may
grow 5 percent in 2012, slower than the 7 percent growth
forecast this year, central bank Deputy Governor Nestor Espenilla said. Remittances from overseas Filipinos help fund
purchases of property and homes.  Banco de Oro Unibank Inc. (BDO)  , the nation’s largest bank by assets, rose 0.4 percent to
53.10 pesos.  Ayala Land Inc. (ALI)  , the largest Philippine
developer, gained 0.2 percent to 16.98 pesos.  Metropolitan Bank & Trust (MBT)  Co: The nation’s
second-largest bank by assets may consider a “larger dividend”
if the lender ends up with excess capital, President Arthur Ty
said. The stock increased 0.2 percent to 68.35 pesos.  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL)  : The
nation’s largest phone company, also known as PLDT, will keep
Digital Telecommunications Philippines Inc. (DGTL PM) as a
separate company and will maintain its services, PLDT spokesman
Ramon Isberto said. Philippine Telephone, which offered to buy
Digital in a deal valued at 74.1 billion pesos ($1.71 billion),
aims to provide broadband services to 95 percent of the country
in three years, Isberto said. Having Digital will make that goal
“faster and cost effective” to achieve, he said. PLDT rose 0.4
percent to 2,350 pesos. Digital gained 0.7 percent to 1.54 pesos.  Semirara Mining Corp. (SCC)  : The nation’s biggest coal
producer was rated “neutral” with a 240 peso 12-month share
price estimate in initial coverage by Jeanette Yutan, an analyst
at JPMorgan Chase & Co. The stock fell 1.5 percent to 212 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
